WEBVTT

1
00:00:47.093 --> 00:00:48.128
Sam?

2
00:00:49.013 --> 00:00:50.731
We drugged him. sir.

3
00:00:51.013 --> 00:00:53.004
It'd be better if he slept.

4
00:00:54.213 --> 00:00:55.931
Didn't see much.

5
00:00:56.733 --> 00:00:59.293
The boys went in. Hit the rocks.

6
00:01:02.733 --> 00:01:04.325
How did it go. Pete?

7
00:01:06.693 --> 00:01:07.967
Fine. Sam.

8
00:01:08.573 --> 00:01:10.245
We take those rocks?

9
00:01:11.333 --> 00:01:12.652
Most of them.

10
00:01:12.813 --> 00:01:14.405
Worst...

11
00:01:14.973 --> 00:01:17.441
ground I ever saw.

12
00:01:17.893 --> 00:01:19.326
You know that?

13
00:01:21.413 --> 00:01:22.892
They call it...

14
00:01:23.533 --> 00:01:26.172
Devil's Den. It's a good name for it.

15
00:01:32.733 --> 00:01:33.768
What casualties?

16
00:01:34.653 --> 00:01:35.642
Don't know yet.

17
00:01:37.533 --> 00:01:39.046
Got to give my boys credit.

18
00:01:43.413 --> 00:01:47.201
You should've let me go to the right.

19
00:01:48.973 --> 00:01:52.602
We should've gone to the right.

20
00:01:53.613 --> 00:01:55.410
He needs to rest some.

21
00:02:54.693 --> 00:02:56.411
You summoned me. sir?

22
00:02:58.253 --> 00:02:59.527
Harrison.

23
00:03:01.773 --> 00:03:03.252
I did.

24
00:03:06.293 --> 00:03:07.806
I've got some night work.

25
00:03:07.893 --> 00:03:08.962
Are you up to it?

26
00:03:09.293 --> 00:03:12.012
"All the world will be in love with night...

27
00:03:12.333 --> 00:03:14.972
"And pay no worship to the garish sun."

28
00:03:16.413 --> 00:03:20.201
When this is all over.
I do look forward to seeing you on stage.

29
00:03:22.213 --> 00:03:24.169
What are the General's wishes?

30
00:03:31.293 --> 00:03:34.569
I want you to go out on the right.
scout the federal position.

31
00:03:34.653 --> 00:03:38.009
Their condition. what they've got
in reserve. what they're bringing up.

32
00:03:38.093 --> 00:03:40.926
It'll probably take all night.
But I want it right and clear.

33
00:03:41.093 --> 00:03:43.402
-Your obedient servant. General.
-Good.

34
00:03:43.653 --> 00:03:47.362
Now. Harrison. it'll be dangerous.
And I do appreciate this.

35
00:03:48.453 --> 00:03:49.806
Thank you. sir.

36
00:03:51.013 --> 00:03:53.891
But I must confess.
the thing that bothers me about this job...

37
00:03:53.973 --> 00:03:55.725
is the absence of an audience.

38
00:03:56.013 --> 00:03:57.844
When you do it right. no one knows it.

39
00:03:57.933 --> 00:04:00.003
Nobody ever watches your work.
Do you see?

40
00:04:01.373 --> 00:04:03.170
That's very hard on an actor.

41
00:04:08.773 --> 00:04:09.762
Go on.

42
00:04:30.333 --> 00:04:32.528
General. I'm very glad to see you well.

43
00:04:32.613 --> 00:04:35.366
I've just come by for my orders. sir.

44
00:04:42.293 --> 00:04:44.648
It would appear
that General Stuart has returned.

45
00:04:46.733 --> 00:04:48.166
The prodigal son.

46
00:05:15.773 --> 00:05:18.207
It was very close this afternoon.

47
00:05:22.413 --> 00:05:23.448
Sir?

48
00:05:23.693 --> 00:05:25.012
They nearly broke.

49
00:05:26.013 --> 00:05:27.685
I could feel them breaking.

50
00:05:28.813 --> 00:05:32.328
There for a moment I thought I saw
our flags go up the hill.

51
00:05:41.053 --> 00:05:42.247
It wasn't that close.

52
00:05:43.413 --> 00:05:46.689
The attacks were not properly
coordinated. I do not know why.

53
00:05:47.373 --> 00:05:49.523
And nevertheless. we nearly won the day.

54
00:05:50.853 --> 00:05:53.970
I could see a clear road
all the way to Washington.

55
00:05:59.213 --> 00:06:00.771
How is it with General Hood?

56
00:06:03.053 --> 00:06:05.408
I think he'll live. May lose an arm.

57
00:06:05.813 --> 00:06:06.882
Dear God.

58
00:06:07.573 --> 00:06:09.723
I couldn't spare General Hood.

59
00:06:11.333 --> 00:06:14.086
So many good men were lost this day.

60
00:06:15.693 --> 00:06:16.682
Sir?

61
00:06:18.333 --> 00:06:21.325
Lo did take the peach orchard
and wheat field.

62
00:06:21.693 --> 00:06:23.729
But he couldn't get up that ridge.

63
00:06:24.653 --> 00:06:29.124
And Hood. he seized the Devil's Den.
but he couldn't take the little rocky hill.

64
00:06:30.413 --> 00:06:33.450
The federals still hold the heights.
And they're reinforced.

65
00:06:34.733 --> 00:06:35.768
General?

66
00:06:37.093 --> 00:06:39.527
That way around to the right is still open.

67
00:06:46.613 --> 00:06:48.331
I will think on it. General.

68
00:06:48.973 --> 00:06:52.488
We have enough artillery
for one more good fight. but just one.

69
00:06:52.653 --> 00:06:53.802
I know.

70
00:06:54.013 --> 00:06:55.412
Let me think on it.

71
00:06:55.853 --> 00:06:58.128
-General--
-I am very glad to see you well.

72
00:06:58.533 --> 00:07:00.285
We will speak again in the morning.

73
00:07:21.653 --> 00:07:24.042
You know. hearing you talk
about monkeys and trees...

74
00:07:24.133 --> 00:07:26.806
I remember the time
during a cannonade on the peninsula.

75
00:07:26.893 --> 00:07:29.361
There was one tree
for the men to hide behind.

76
00:07:29.453 --> 00:07:33.128
It was a skinny little tree
and the boys. they fell in behind it...

77
00:07:33.213 --> 00:07:36.444
in a long thin line
which ruled just like a pigtail.

78
00:07:36.533 --> 00:07:38.410
It swayed to one side. then the other.

79
00:07:38.533 --> 00:07:40.763
A shell came this way.
the line swayed that way.

80
00:07:40.853 --> 00:07:43.367
A cannonball came that way.
the line swayed this way.

81
00:07:43.453 --> 00:07:44.727
It was a thing to see.

82
00:07:44.813 --> 00:07:48.010
George. what has that got to do
with what we're talking about?

83
00:07:53.933 --> 00:07:54.922
General.

84
00:07:57.453 --> 00:08:00.251
Carry on. gentlemen.
Don't let me interrupt the revival.

85
00:08:00.573 --> 00:08:02.245
General. you're just in time.

86
00:08:03.293 --> 00:08:07.445
I've been trying to persuade George here
of the modern. scientific...

87
00:08:07.533 --> 00:08:10.093
theories of Charles Darwin.
The theory of evolution.

88
00:08:10.173 --> 00:08:13.131
The notion that all mankind
is descended from the ape.

89
00:08:13.853 --> 00:08:15.650
He does not subscribe.

90
00:08:15.733 --> 00:08:17.052
-Is that so?
-I do not.

91
00:08:17.133 --> 00:08:20.967
I've ordered General Armistead to stop
filling his head with heathen blasphemies.

92
00:08:21.053 --> 00:08:23.772
Now. you are to devote
your reflective moments to study...

93
00:08:23.853 --> 00:08:26.048
in the matters of military significance.

94
00:08:26.213 --> 00:08:27.202
Ordered me.

95
00:08:27.573 --> 00:08:31.122
Or perhaps appropriating
some more of this fine whiskey here.

96
00:08:31.213 --> 00:08:32.202
Absolutely.

97
00:08:32.533 --> 00:08:34.330
-Would you care for?
-No. thank you.

98
00:08:34.413 --> 00:08:37.485
Surely the commanding general
shares my deep feelings of disgust...

99
00:08:37.613 --> 00:08:39.410
at this simian suggestion.

100
00:08:41.533 --> 00:08:45.208
I suppose there's some pretty smart folk
that take Darwin for the Gospel.

101
00:08:45.973 --> 00:08:50.524
They would not be invited to join
George's ever-shrinking circle of friends.

102
00:08:50.613 --> 00:08:52.365
General Longstreet. sir.

103
00:08:52.613 --> 00:08:56.003
I intend to lay this matter to rest
for once and for all time.

104
00:08:56.213 --> 00:08:57.202
Good.

105
00:09:02.613 --> 00:09:06.731
Perhaps there are those among you who
think that you are descended from an ape.

106
00:09:08.493 --> 00:09:10.723
I suppose it's possible
there are those of you...

107
00:09:10.813 --> 00:09:13.327
who believe that I'm descended
from an ape. but...

108
00:09:13.413 --> 00:09:15.608
I challenge the man to step forward...

109
00:09:16.533 --> 00:09:19.445
who believes that General Lee
is descended from an ape.

110
00:09:19.693 --> 00:09:21.012
-Here. here.
-Not likely.

111
00:09:22.253 --> 00:09:26.724
All science trembles before
the searing logic of your fiery intellect.

112
00:09:37.173 --> 00:09:40.529
So. exactly how many of your relatives
are there that are apes?

113
00:09:50.293 --> 00:09:52.648
What do you hear about Sam Hood?

114
00:09:53.093 --> 00:09:54.572
He may lose an arm.

115
00:09:56.093 --> 00:09:58.891
Dick Garnett isn't fit. Can't hardly walk.

116
00:09:59.413 --> 00:10:02.849
Thing is. if there's a fight.
he can't stand to stay out of it.

117
00:10:03.373 --> 00:10:05.329
But if you ordered him to stay out....

118
00:10:08.973 --> 00:10:11.009
I don't suppose you could do that.

119
00:10:40.973 --> 00:10:42.406
That boy can sing.

120
00:10:43.773 --> 00:10:45.843
That's <i>Kathleen Mavourneen</i>.

121
00:10:51.893 --> 00:10:54.088
What do you hear about Hancock?

122
00:10:54.893 --> 00:10:56.292
Ran into him today.

123
00:10:58.533 --> 00:11:00.330
He's out there about a mile or so.

124
00:11:00.773 --> 00:11:04.652
Just a mile or so. And he was tough.

125
00:11:05.293 --> 00:11:06.567
Very tough today.

126
00:11:06.973 --> 00:11:08.804
He's the best they got.

127
00:11:09.173 --> 00:11:11.528
God don't make them any better.
And that's a fact.

128
00:11:16.693 --> 00:11:19.332
I'd like to go over to see him
as soon as I can.

129
00:11:22.093 --> 00:11:24.129
The last time I saw Winn...

130
00:11:26.253 --> 00:11:29.370
he played that song. That very song.

131
00:11:31.013 --> 00:11:34.323
Back in California.
we were all together for the last time.

132
00:11:35.133 --> 00:11:36.771
Before we broke up.

133
00:11:37.693 --> 00:11:39.411
Spring of 1861.

134
00:11:46.533 --> 00:11:47.682
Myra Hancock.

135
00:11:48.213 --> 00:11:50.807
Do you remember Myra. Hancock's wife?

136
00:11:51.413 --> 00:11:52.812
Beautiful woman.

137
00:11:53.173 --> 00:11:56.085
Most perfect woman I ever saw.

138
00:11:58.613 --> 00:12:00.126
They were a beautiful couple.

139
00:12:01.893 --> 00:12:02.882
Beautiful.

140
00:12:06.373 --> 00:12:08.250
Garnett was with me that night.

141
00:12:10.253 --> 00:12:14.326
A lot of fellows from the old outfit.
People standing around singing...

142
00:12:14.733 --> 00:12:16.007
in the blue uniform.

143
00:12:16.653 --> 00:12:19.326
We were leaving the next day.

144
00:12:20.253 --> 00:12:22.847
Some going north. Some going south.

145
00:12:24.693 --> 00:12:25.921
Splitting up.

146
00:12:29.013 --> 00:12:30.571
A soldier's farewell.

147
00:12:31.453 --> 00:12:33.364
"Goodbye. Good luck.

148
00:12:34.333 --> 00:12:35.846
"I'll see you in hell."

149
00:12:37.253 --> 00:12:38.732
Do you remember that?

150
00:12:46.413 --> 00:12:48.369
Towards the end of the evening...

151
00:12:49.533 --> 00:12:51.728
we all sat around the piano.

152
00:12:53.213 --> 00:12:55.329
And Myra played...

153
00:12:56.493 --> 00:12:59.371
that song there.
that was the one she played.

154
00:13:02.213 --> 00:13:05.046
Maybe for years. maybe forever...

155
00:13:07.973 --> 00:13:09.406
I'll never forget that.

156
00:13:15.173 --> 00:13:16.970
You know how it was. Pete.

157
00:13:25.373 --> 00:13:27.045
Winn was like a brother to me.

158
00:13:27.373 --> 00:13:28.362
Remember?

159
00:13:30.533 --> 00:13:32.330
Towards the end of the evening...

160
00:13:35.133 --> 00:13:36.646
things got a little rough.

161
00:13:37.133 --> 00:13:39.203
We all began to....

162
00:13:44.013 --> 00:13:45.969
There were a lot of tears.

163
00:13:49.453 --> 00:13:51.011
I went over to Hancock.

164
00:13:52.533 --> 00:13:54.524
I took him by the shoulder. I said:

165
00:13:57.693 --> 00:13:59.046
"So help me...

166
00:14:00.333 --> 00:14:02.847
"if I ever raise my hand against you...

167
00:14:03.693 --> 00:14:05.126
"may God strike me dead."

168
00:14:13.413 --> 00:14:15.051
I haven't seen him since.

169
00:14:16.293 --> 00:14:18.170
He was at Malvern Hill...

170
00:14:18.573 --> 00:14:22.407
White Oak Swamp.
Sharpsburg. Fredericksburg.

171
00:14:26.893 --> 00:14:30.283
One of these days
I will see him. I'm afraid.

172
00:14:31.533 --> 00:14:33.012
Across that...

173
00:14:34.093 --> 00:14:36.732
small deadly space.

174
00:14:45.013 --> 00:14:48.244
I thought about sitting this one out.

175
00:14:48.573 --> 00:14:50.086
But I can't do that.

176
00:14:51.733 --> 00:14:53.724
That wouldn't be right either.

177
00:15:00.373 --> 00:15:01.362
I guess not.

178
00:15:06.573 --> 00:15:07.972
Thank you. Peter.

179
00:15:12.293 --> 00:15:14.045
I had to talk about that.

180
00:15:21.293 --> 00:15:24.126
I'm sending Myra Hancock...

181
00:15:25.533 --> 00:15:28.411
a small package to be opened...

182
00:15:29.293 --> 00:15:31.045
in the event of my death.

183
00:15:36.253 --> 00:15:37.766
You'll drop by and see her...

184
00:15:38.333 --> 00:15:39.846
after this is over.

185
00:15:40.493 --> 00:15:41.846
Won't you. Pete?

186
00:15:50.573 --> 00:15:51.688
Thank you.

187
00:15:55.173 --> 00:15:56.811
What day is it now. Major?

188
00:15:59.973 --> 00:16:01.850
It's long after midnight. sir.

189
00:16:02.053 --> 00:16:03.372
It's already Friday.

190
00:16:03.573 --> 00:16:05.962
-Friday. July 3?
-Yes. sir.

191
00:16:07.053 --> 00:16:09.123
Then tomorrow is the Fourth of July.

192
00:16:10.413 --> 00:16:11.812
Independence Day.

193
00:16:14.893 --> 00:16:18.124
-I'd quite forgotten.
-The good Lord has a sense of humor.

194
00:16:18.733 --> 00:16:20.883
I'm very sorry to keep you up so late.

195
00:16:20.973 --> 00:16:22.326
It is my pleasure.

196
00:16:22.453 --> 00:16:24.330
We should have a larger staff.

197
00:16:24.933 --> 00:16:26.651
I'd be offended. sir.

198
00:16:27.413 --> 00:16:28.846
I can do the work.

199
00:16:28.933 --> 00:16:30.048
Very well.

200
00:16:32.373 --> 00:16:34.933
General Stuart is waiting to see you. sir.

201
00:16:35.773 --> 00:16:38.651
-Shall I bring him in?
-Of course.

202
00:16:41.533 --> 00:16:43.205
-Major?
-Yes. sir.

203
00:16:43.573 --> 00:16:46.292
General Stuart and I
must not be disturbed.

204
00:16:47.533 --> 00:16:49.444
-Very well. sir.
-Thank you.

205
00:16:52.853 --> 00:16:55.208
General Lee will see you now. sir.

206
00:17:06.493 --> 00:17:07.846
You wish to see me. sir.

207
00:17:12.853 --> 00:17:18.166
It is the opinion of some excellent officers
that you have let us all down.

208
00:17:19.053 --> 00:17:21.772
Sir. if you will please tell me
who these gentlemen are?

209
00:17:21.853 --> 00:17:23.969
There will be none of that.
There is no time.

210
00:17:24.053 --> 00:17:26.009
I ask that I be allowed to defend my--

211
00:17:26.093 --> 00:17:27.492
There is no time.

212
00:17:29.253 --> 00:17:30.288
General Stuart.

213
00:17:33.213 --> 00:17:36.603
Your mission was to free this army...

214
00:17:37.133 --> 00:17:38.771
from the enemy cavalry.

215
00:17:38.853 --> 00:17:42.129
And to report any movement
by the enemy's main body.

216
00:17:42.373 --> 00:17:44.011
That mission was not fulfilled.

217
00:17:44.533 --> 00:17:46.091
You left here...

218
00:17:46.253 --> 00:17:49.962
with no word of your movement
or movement of the enemy for days.

219
00:17:50.213 --> 00:17:52.568
Meanwhile we were engaged
and drawn into battle...

220
00:17:52.813 --> 00:17:56.203
without adequate knowledge
of the enemy's strength or position.

221
00:17:56.293 --> 00:17:57.931
Without knowledge of the ground.

222
00:17:58.093 --> 00:18:01.722
So it is only by God's grace
that we did not meet disaster here.

223
00:18:02.333 --> 00:18:03.971
General Lee. there were reasons.

224
00:18:04.133 --> 00:18:06.966
Perhaps you misunderstood my orders.

225
00:18:08.013 --> 00:18:10.402
Perhaps I did not make myself clear.

226
00:18:11.053 --> 00:18:14.762
Well. sir. this must be made very clear.

227
00:18:15.613 --> 00:18:16.932
You. sir...

228
00:18:17.133 --> 00:18:20.170
with your cavalry.
are the eyes of this army.

229
00:18:20.853 --> 00:18:23.447
Without your cavalry. we are made blind.

230
00:18:23.773 --> 00:18:25.764
That has already happened once.

231
00:18:25.933 --> 00:18:29.289
It must never. never happen again.

232
00:18:37.933 --> 00:18:41.687
-Since I no longer hold the General's--
-I told you there is no time for that!

233
00:18:41.813 --> 00:18:42.882
There is no time.

234
00:18:59.013 --> 00:19:02.164
There is another fight coming tomorrow
and we need you.

235
00:19:02.253 --> 00:19:04.369
We need every man. God knows.

236
00:19:07.053 --> 00:19:09.362
You must take what I have told you...

237
00:19:10.093 --> 00:19:13.051
and learn from it as a man does.

238
00:19:14.573 --> 00:19:16.052
There has been a mistake.

239
00:19:16.133 --> 00:19:18.966
It will not happen again.
I know your quality.

240
00:19:19.373 --> 00:19:22.445
You are one of the finest
cavalry officers I have ever known...

241
00:19:22.613 --> 00:19:25.969
and your service to this army
has been invaluable.

242
00:19:31.933 --> 00:19:34.049
Let us speak no more of this.

243
00:19:42.493 --> 00:19:45.530
The matter is concluded.
Goodnight. General.

244
00:20:24.373 --> 00:20:25.772
Colonel. sir.

245
00:20:29.773 --> 00:20:31.525
What are you doing up here?

246
00:20:32.213 --> 00:20:34.090
I'm just resting my leg.

247
00:20:38.573 --> 00:20:39.847
All right.

248
00:20:42.333 --> 00:20:44.210
You sure can see a ways from here.

249
00:20:46.253 --> 00:20:47.845
Where have you been?

250
00:20:48.493 --> 00:20:50.051
We sent out a detail...

251
00:20:50.333 --> 00:20:52.688
and found some more departed souls
down there...

252
00:20:52.773 --> 00:20:55.845
and they were carrying coffee
for which they had no more use for.

253
00:20:55.933 --> 00:20:56.922
You're a ghoul.

254
00:21:01.933 --> 00:21:03.969
You did real good yesterday.

255
00:21:05.173 --> 00:21:07.403
The way them rebs just kept coming.

256
00:21:09.013 --> 00:21:10.810
You had to admire them.

257
00:21:12.733 --> 00:21:14.485
You think they'll come again today?

258
00:21:15.613 --> 00:21:18.127
It don't look like they're planning to leave.

259
00:21:19.213 --> 00:21:20.646
We don't have but 100 men.

260
00:21:20.893 --> 00:21:23.361
Even with the whole flock
from the Second Maine.

261
00:21:23.693 --> 00:21:25.285
This position's good.

262
00:21:30.933 --> 00:21:32.048
Diversion.

263
00:21:34.253 --> 00:21:35.811
Go alert the pickets.

264
00:21:35.893 --> 00:21:38.612
That may be a diversion.
They may be coming this way again.

265
00:21:38.853 --> 00:21:40.650
Where's the ammunition I asked for?

266
00:21:40.733 --> 00:21:43.452
Go check the hospital. see about the boys.
Check on Buster.

267
00:21:43.533 --> 00:21:45.046
Very well. sir.

268
00:21:45.213 --> 00:21:46.726
We need another runner.

269
00:21:46.813 --> 00:21:50.567
I keep going up and down this hill.
my legs are going to fall off.

270
00:21:56.013 --> 00:21:58.083
-Good morning. General.
-Good morning. sir.

271
00:21:58.173 --> 00:22:00.892
-Ride with me. if you will.
-Yes. sir.

272
00:22:29.733 --> 00:22:32.805
General Longstreet. you have
General Pickett now and he is fresh.

273
00:22:33.293 --> 00:22:35.443
I want you to bring your corps forward.

274
00:22:35.693 --> 00:22:39.368
Take those heights in the center
and split the federal line.

275
00:22:47.013 --> 00:22:49.652
My two divisions. Hood's and McLaws'....

276
00:22:50.133 --> 00:22:53.808
They executed a forced march yesterday
and went straight into the fight.

277
00:22:54.053 --> 00:22:55.771
Lost half of their strength.

278
00:22:56.613 --> 00:22:58.729
Sustained 50% casualties. sir.

279
00:22:58.893 --> 00:23:00.963
They are tired and need rest.

280
00:23:02.893 --> 00:23:04.008
There are...

281
00:23:04.693 --> 00:23:08.242
now three federal corps on those two
rocky hills on our right flank.

282
00:23:08.333 --> 00:23:10.608
If I move all my people forward...

283
00:23:10.853 --> 00:23:13.128
we won't have a flank at all.

284
00:23:13.293 --> 00:23:15.329
They'll simply swing around and crush us.

285
00:23:17.493 --> 00:23:20.166
They are well entrenched up there.
They aim to fight.

286
00:23:20.253 --> 00:23:22.926
They got good artillery and plenty of it.

287
00:23:23.373 --> 00:23:26.331
Sir. any attack we make
will be uphill over open ground.

288
00:23:27.493 --> 00:23:30.246
How do we communicate?
How do we coordinate attack?

289
00:23:30.853 --> 00:23:33.367
They're all massed together.
damned near in a circle.

290
00:23:33.533 --> 00:23:35.046
Good interior lines.

291
00:23:35.653 --> 00:23:38.690
Anywhere we hit them.
they'll bring up reinforcements in minutes.

292
00:23:39.373 --> 00:23:43.127
But we try to bring up support.
it has to come from miles away.

293
00:23:43.693 --> 00:23:45.411
Their cannon will see every move.

294
00:23:46.693 --> 00:23:49.605
Hell. their cannon are looking down
on us right now.

295
00:23:50.333 --> 00:23:52.130
In the center. they will break.

296
00:23:53.413 --> 00:23:55.210
They will break in the center.

297
00:23:55.293 --> 00:23:59.002
They'll be gaining men from all directions.
guns by the thousands...

298
00:23:59.093 --> 00:24:02.449
and Richmond has nothing left
to send us. So. if we stay. we fight.

299
00:24:03.053 --> 00:24:06.409
If we retreat now.
we will have fought here for two days...

300
00:24:06.653 --> 00:24:09.247
and will leave knowing
we could not drive him off.

301
00:24:10.053 --> 00:24:14.410
And I have never yet left the enemy
in command of the field. No. sir.

302
00:24:14.733 --> 00:24:16.644
Retreat is no longer an option.

303
00:24:17.773 --> 00:24:20.003
The enemy has been attacked
on both wings.

304
00:24:20.133 --> 00:24:21.532
He has reinforced there...

305
00:24:21.613 --> 00:24:24.685
and is strongest there on the wings.
The hills and the rocks.

306
00:24:24.773 --> 00:24:26.570
So the weak point is in the center.

307
00:24:26.653 --> 00:24:28.609
They have command of the high ground.

308
00:24:28.693 --> 00:24:31.048
But in that long slope. you see there?

309
00:24:31.253 --> 00:24:34.928
The long slope in the center.
there's where he's most vulnerable.

310
00:24:35.373 --> 00:24:39.207
General Pickett's Virginians
are the only people not yet engaged. Yes?

311
00:24:40.813 --> 00:24:43.850
With General Longstreet in command.
my old warhorse...

312
00:24:44.093 --> 00:24:47.130
meeting the enemy face to face
on ground of his choosing...

313
00:24:47.213 --> 00:24:49.283
and with honor. we will prevail.

314
00:25:08.333 --> 00:25:10.642
Sir. a courier from Colonel Rice.

315
00:25:14.013 --> 00:25:15.207
Colonel Chamberlain.

316
00:25:18.573 --> 00:25:19.926
That's some climb. sir.

317
00:25:20.173 --> 00:25:21.765
My men need rations. Lieutenant.

318
00:25:22.213 --> 00:25:25.444
Colonel Rice has entrusted me to tell you
that you're relieved. sir.

319
00:25:26.973 --> 00:25:28.008
Relieved?

320
00:25:28.173 --> 00:25:31.449
Fresh troops are on their way up
and they'll take over here. sir.

321
00:25:32.093 --> 00:25:34.561
Colonel Rice wants to give
your people a rest.

322
00:25:34.853 --> 00:25:37.367
He wants you to fall back.
and I'm to show you the way.

323
00:25:37.453 --> 00:25:38.727
Fall back.

324
00:25:41.293 --> 00:25:43.443
Ellis. have the men fall in.
We're moving out.

325
00:25:43.533 --> 00:25:44.602
Yes. sir.

326
00:25:45.453 --> 00:25:46.568
Where are we going?

327
00:25:48.093 --> 00:25:49.287
Lovely spot.

328
00:25:49.533 --> 00:25:51.728
Very quiet. Safest place on the battlefield.

329
00:25:52.013 --> 00:25:53.810
Right smack-dab in the center.

330
00:26:37.093 --> 00:26:38.526
Yes. sir. General.

331
00:26:39.093 --> 00:26:40.446
We will attack the center.

332
00:26:41.213 --> 00:26:43.329
But I think you are right about the flank.

333
00:26:44.533 --> 00:26:47.684
Hood and McLaws were both very badly
damaged yesterday.

334
00:26:48.493 --> 00:26:52.771
I'll give you two other divisions:
General Pettigrew and General Trimble.

335
00:26:52.853 --> 00:26:54.366
They are stronger and rested.

336
00:26:54.453 --> 00:26:58.492
Now. you will have nearly three divisions
at your command. including Pickett.

337
00:26:58.733 --> 00:27:01.611
Your objective will be
that clump of trees yonder.

338
00:27:04.093 --> 00:27:06.732
The attack will be preceded
by massed artillery.

339
00:27:06.893 --> 00:27:10.090
We'll concentrate all of our guns
on that one small area.

340
00:27:10.333 --> 00:27:13.006
A <i>feu d'enfer</i>. as Napoleon would call it.

341
00:27:13.653 --> 00:27:17.328
When the artillery has had its effect.
your charge will break the line.

342
00:27:17.413 --> 00:27:20.803
You will have nearly 15.000 men
at your command. General.

343
00:27:21.133 --> 00:27:23.124
You may begin whenever you're ready.

344
00:27:23.213 --> 00:27:25.932
But plan it well.
Do plan it well. I pray you. sir.

345
00:27:26.133 --> 00:27:27.964
We stake everything on this.

346
00:27:28.173 --> 00:27:29.925
With your permission.

347
00:27:34.453 --> 00:27:36.683
Sir. I've been a soldier all my life.

348
00:27:36.973 --> 00:27:39.965
I have served from the ranks on up.
You know my service.

349
00:27:44.173 --> 00:27:47.609
I must tell you now.
I believe this attack will fail.

350
00:27:52.293 --> 00:27:55.808
No 15.000 men ever made
can take that ridge.

351
00:27:56.333 --> 00:27:58.893
It's a distance of more than a mile
over open ground.

352
00:27:58.973 --> 00:28:01.282
When the men come out of the trees
they will be...

353
00:28:01.653 --> 00:28:04.725
under fire of Yankee artillery
from all over the field.

354
00:28:04.813 --> 00:28:06.166
Those are Hancock's boys.

355
00:28:06.613 --> 00:28:10.447
And now they have the stone wall
like we did at Fredericksburg.

356
00:28:11.253 --> 00:28:13.130
We do our duty. General.

357
00:28:13.933 --> 00:28:15.844
We do what we must do.

358
00:28:16.853 --> 00:28:17.842
Yes. sir.

359
00:28:19.693 --> 00:28:23.322
Colonel Alexander is in charge
of the artillery and he is very good.

360
00:28:24.493 --> 00:28:28.805
We will depend on him to drive them off
the ridge before your divisions get there.

361
00:28:29.293 --> 00:28:32.205
And the men will know what to do.
All 15.000...

362
00:28:32.293 --> 00:28:36.127
will concentrate squarely on the center
of that line. That lower ridge there.

363
00:28:36.333 --> 00:28:38.403
The line is not strong there.

364
00:28:38.653 --> 00:28:41.611
General Meade has great strength
on both flanks.

365
00:28:42.053 --> 00:28:43.930
He must be weak in the center.

366
00:28:44.013 --> 00:28:47.926
I estimate his strength in the center
not to be more than 5.000 men.

367
00:28:48.173 --> 00:28:52.291
And Colonel Alexander's artillery
will break them up like at Fredericksburg.

368
00:28:52.773 --> 00:28:54.445
-Yes. sir.
-Farewell.

369
00:29:02.493 --> 00:29:04.085
What are you thinking. General?

370
00:29:09.293 --> 00:29:11.409
Pickett's division is from my corps.

371
00:29:11.493 --> 00:29:14.371
But the other two units
are of A.P. Hill's corps.

372
00:29:18.573 --> 00:29:20.529
Shouldn't General Hill lead the attack?

373
00:29:21.853 --> 00:29:22.842
Say again?

374
00:29:24.813 --> 00:29:27.247
Shouldn't General Hill lead the attack?

375
00:29:36.173 --> 00:29:37.288
My apologies. sir.

376
00:29:41.933 --> 00:29:44.288
I've always been very cautious.

377
00:29:44.693 --> 00:29:45.887
Very cautious.

378
00:29:45.973 --> 00:29:47.850
There is no one I trust more.

379
00:29:55.253 --> 00:29:57.448
If we can take that ridge....

380
00:29:57.693 --> 00:29:59.923
We can. And we will.

381
00:30:06.893 --> 00:30:09.612
General. God go with you.

382
00:30:29.373 --> 00:30:31.170
George. you are leading attack.

383
00:30:31.253 --> 00:30:32.606
Now get ready. George.

384
00:30:32.773 --> 00:30:35.890
Take your men behind the line of trees.
I'll give you details later.

385
00:30:35.973 --> 00:30:37.565
Now. move. George!

386
00:33:34.773 --> 00:33:38.925
Forgive me the torn trousers. sir.
An officer riding around like this.

387
00:33:39.453 --> 00:33:40.886
Colonel Alexander.

388
00:33:41.533 --> 00:33:45.572
Those federal cannon up on that
little rocky hill can cause some trouble.

389
00:33:45.933 --> 00:33:48.891
I want you to assign some guns
and keep them silent.

390
00:33:48.973 --> 00:33:49.962
Then...

391
00:33:50.053 --> 00:33:52.487
you move forward
when the infantry advance...

392
00:33:52.573 --> 00:33:54.165
keeping the flanks clear.

393
00:33:54.373 --> 00:33:55.886
Porter. how old are you. son?

394
00:33:56.053 --> 00:33:57.327
Sir. I'm 28. sir.

395
00:33:59.893 --> 00:34:04.045
Porter. we must also clear those guns
off that low center ridge right there.

396
00:34:04.133 --> 00:34:06.363
-That is the main thing.
-Yes. sir.

397
00:34:06.493 --> 00:34:09.690
-I'm relying on you. son.
-Yes. sir. I'll sure keep them shooting.

398
00:34:09.773 --> 00:34:10.922
Good.

399
00:34:12.013 --> 00:34:13.890
I want you to use everything you have.

400
00:34:13.973 --> 00:34:16.282
Maximum effort.
Fire all long-range ordinance.

401
00:34:16.373 --> 00:34:19.490
But don't open up till I give the word
and everything's in position.

402
00:34:19.893 --> 00:34:23.249
Then fire with all you've got.
I don't want to see a single gun silent.

403
00:34:23.493 --> 00:34:25.723
Find an observation point
and check the damage.

404
00:34:25.813 --> 00:34:27.963
We must clear those people off that ridge.

405
00:34:30.133 --> 00:34:31.452
If we don't....

406
00:34:31.893 --> 00:34:35.249
Anyway. you let me know when you're
nearing the end of your ammunition.

407
00:34:35.453 --> 00:34:38.968
We must conserve enough to support
the infantry attack. Is that clear?

408
00:34:39.213 --> 00:34:40.202
Yes. sir.

409
00:35:19.653 --> 00:35:22.372
Johnston Pettigrew.
University of North Carolina.

410
00:35:23.453 --> 00:35:24.602
Yeah. I know.

411
00:35:25.173 --> 00:35:28.131
They still talk about your grades there
with reverence and awe.

412
00:35:28.213 --> 00:35:31.330
Your reputation as a scholar
has preceded you. sir.

413
00:35:31.573 --> 00:35:33.131
I hear you've written a book.

414
00:35:33.213 --> 00:35:36.205
It was only a minor work.
If the general would care to read it....

415
00:35:36.813 --> 00:35:39.532
-Surely.
-Take a copy with my compliments.

416
00:35:39.613 --> 00:35:41.968
Captain. retrieve my book
from the baggage.

417
00:35:42.053 --> 00:35:45.841
General. my apologies. but I do not believe
I will have time to read that today.

418
00:35:47.933 --> 00:35:49.048
Gentlemen.

419
00:35:50.453 --> 00:35:53.206
I want you to look
at that clump of trees on that ridge.

420
00:35:54.773 --> 00:35:57.606
That is where all units will converge.

421
00:35:58.413 --> 00:36:02.929
You will be spread out in a long line.
perhaps a mile. about 15.000 men.

422
00:36:03.333 --> 00:36:06.689
All units converging on that point
on the crest of that ridge.

423
00:36:07.293 --> 00:36:08.772
Now. look here.

424
00:36:13.973 --> 00:36:16.203
The Yankee center. A stone wall.

425
00:36:18.693 --> 00:36:20.206
A small grove of trees.

426
00:36:21.973 --> 00:36:25.488
General Trimble. commanding
Pender's division. will be on the left.

427
00:36:26.893 --> 00:36:28.929
Pettigrew's brigade in support.

428
00:36:30.453 --> 00:36:33.650
General Pickett's division
will be on the right side of the attack.

429
00:36:33.973 --> 00:36:37.682
And now. George.
I want you to put two brigades in front...

430
00:36:37.933 --> 00:36:39.764
and one in back. like so.

431
00:36:40.333 --> 00:36:41.322
Yes. sir.

432
00:36:42.573 --> 00:36:43.801
Garnett's brigade.

433
00:36:43.933 --> 00:36:45.412
That's Jimmy Kemper.

434
00:36:45.773 --> 00:36:47.491
Armistead's in support.

435
00:36:48.373 --> 00:36:49.965
Good. All right. then.

436
00:36:50.133 --> 00:36:52.169
Garnett will dress off at Trimble's flank.

437
00:36:52.253 --> 00:36:55.563
And he will be the hinge. so to speak.
in a series of left obliques.

438
00:36:56.453 --> 00:36:58.523
Somewhere about
the Emmitsburgh Road...

439
00:36:58.653 --> 00:37:01.372
you will execute your first left oblique.

440
00:37:01.893 --> 00:37:03.087
Then direct.

441
00:37:03.373 --> 00:37:04.522
Then left again.

442
00:37:04.853 --> 00:37:06.889
And so on at your own discretion...

443
00:37:07.093 --> 00:37:11.211
in order to deceive the Yankees
and spread them out in a long line.

444
00:37:11.533 --> 00:37:12.886
Here. Any questions?

445
00:37:14.973 --> 00:37:16.452
All right. gentlemen.

446
00:37:21.613 --> 00:37:24.605
That is the conversion point.
That clump of trees.

447
00:37:25.173 --> 00:37:27.164
We will use all of the artillery.

448
00:37:28.133 --> 00:37:31.330
And it will center on the point. right there.

449
00:37:32.293 --> 00:37:35.524
We'll fire every gun they have
until the ammunition runs out.

450
00:37:36.533 --> 00:37:39.969
When that is done.
I will give the order and you all go in.

451
00:37:49.173 --> 00:37:53.007
I do believe this attack will decide
the fate of our country.

452
00:37:54.613 --> 00:37:59.812
All the men who have died in the past
are with you here today.

453
00:38:10.093 --> 00:38:15.087
I want to say. sir. it is an honor to serve
under your command.

454
00:38:23.373 --> 00:38:26.763
I want to thank you. sir. for giving me
the opportunity of serving here.

455
00:38:26.853 --> 00:38:29.321
I have prayed. sir.

456
00:39:04.413 --> 00:39:05.812
Can you take that ridge?

457
00:39:28.213 --> 00:39:29.202
Harrison.

458
00:39:29.613 --> 00:39:32.525
Would you mind giving someone an order
to give me a musket?

459
00:39:32.613 --> 00:39:34.683
I think today I'd like to join the attack.

460
00:39:35.013 --> 00:39:39.052
If I could even borrow a hat from a soldier
or just a jacket with some stripes on it.

461
00:39:40.533 --> 00:39:41.807
Sir. just once.

462
00:39:42.333 --> 00:39:45.405
Because I think. sir.
today might be the last day.

463
00:39:49.733 --> 00:39:51.371
Haven't I earned it. sir?

464
00:39:55.133 --> 00:39:56.805
You know what's going to happen?

465
00:40:02.373 --> 00:40:04.284
I'll tell you what's going to happen.

466
00:40:06.133 --> 00:40:08.772
Troops are now forming
behind the line of trees.

467
00:40:09.893 --> 00:40:15.411
When they come out. they will be under
enemy long-range artillery fire.

468
00:40:16.053 --> 00:40:19.125
Solid shot. Percussion.
Every gun they have.

469
00:40:21.213 --> 00:40:24.091
Troops will come out under fire
with more than a mile to walk.

470
00:40:24.533 --> 00:40:26.569
And still. within the open field...

471
00:40:27.093 --> 00:40:29.163
among the range of aimed muskets.

472
00:40:42.373 --> 00:40:45.251
They'll be slowed down
by that fence out there.

473
00:40:45.813 --> 00:40:49.522
And the formation. what's left of it.
will begin to come apart.

474
00:40:51.333 --> 00:40:55.087
When they cross that road.
they'll be under short-range artillery.

475
00:40:55.493 --> 00:40:56.926
Canister fire.

476
00:40:57.293 --> 00:41:00.729
Thousands of little bits of shrapnel
wiping the holes in the lines.

477
00:41:02.933 --> 00:41:05.401
If they get to that wall
without breaking up...

478
00:41:06.533 --> 00:41:08.125
there won't be many left.

479
00:41:11.253 --> 00:41:13.005
A mathematical equation.

480
00:41:15.533 --> 00:41:18.491
But maybe. just maybe...

481
00:41:19.733 --> 00:41:22.122
our own artillery will break up
their defenses.

482
00:41:23.373 --> 00:41:25.011
There's always that hope.

483
00:41:29.933 --> 00:41:32.891
That's Hancock out there.
And he isn't going to run.

484
00:41:35.733 --> 00:41:37.451
So it's mathematical after all.

485
00:41:38.933 --> 00:41:43.723
If they get to that road. or beyond it.
we'll suffer over 50 percent casualties.

486
00:41:48.853 --> 00:41:50.172
But. Harrison...

487
00:41:52.533 --> 00:41:55.331
I don't believe my boys will reach
that wall.

488
00:42:06.493 --> 00:42:08.449
Sir. with your permission.

489
00:42:11.973 --> 00:42:14.282
I'll get myself that musket. sir.

490
00:42:25.253 --> 00:42:26.891
That's General Meade's headquarters.

491
00:42:28.093 --> 00:42:29.924
You're to take a position in reserve.

492
00:42:31.173 --> 00:42:34.290
You don't have to entrench.
but please don't go away.

493
00:42:34.373 --> 00:42:37.445
-Major Spear. do you have that?
-Yes. sir. I'll place the men.

494
00:42:37.533 --> 00:42:41.242
You. sir. are to report to General Hancock.
If you will follow me.

495
00:42:52.613 --> 00:42:55.571
General Hancock. sir.
Colonel Chamberlain. 20th Maine.

496
00:42:55.733 --> 00:42:56.722
Chamberlain.

497
00:42:56.813 --> 00:42:57.802
Yes.

498
00:42:58.133 --> 00:43:00.931
I hear from the ranks that
you may have been more involved...

499
00:43:01.013 --> 00:43:02.924
than anyone in staff has told me.

500
00:43:03.013 --> 00:43:04.332
We were involved.

501
00:43:04.533 --> 00:43:06.922
They tell me
you ordered a bayonet charge.

502
00:43:07.253 --> 00:43:09.562
It's nothing to be ashamed of.
I might tell you.

503
00:43:11.453 --> 00:43:12.852
I'm going to look into it.

504
00:43:13.053 --> 00:43:15.089
We need fighting men in this army.

505
00:43:15.253 --> 00:43:18.165
And one damn thing is sure.
we'll need some brigade commanders.

506
00:43:19.573 --> 00:43:21.529
Meanwhile. well done. Well done.

507
00:43:21.613 --> 00:43:23.012
Thank you. sir.

508
00:43:23.093 --> 00:43:24.446
How's your outfit?

509
00:43:24.933 --> 00:43:27.925
We need provisions.
The men need a meal. And ammunition.

510
00:43:28.053 --> 00:43:29.042
We're out.

511
00:43:29.373 --> 00:43:31.568
See to Colonel Chamberlain's request.

512
00:43:32.093 --> 00:43:33.765
I want you to write a report.

513
00:43:33.853 --> 00:43:34.922
Yes. sir.

514
00:43:38.373 --> 00:43:40.364
They say you are a schoolteacher.

515
00:43:41.013 --> 00:43:43.163
That seems like a long time ago.

516
00:43:43.253 --> 00:43:45.813
Sometimes I'm not sure
how long I've been in this war.

517
00:43:45.893 --> 00:43:48.088
Three years or three lifetimes.

518
00:43:48.493 --> 00:43:50.211
-What do you teach?
-Rhetoric...

519
00:43:50.453 --> 00:43:54.048
and Natural and Revealed Religion.
At Bowdoin College. sir.

520
00:43:55.613 --> 00:43:57.331
Now you tell me. Professor.

521
00:43:59.253 --> 00:44:01.847
Can you recall a story from antiquity
where two men...

522
00:44:01.933 --> 00:44:04.083
who are best of friends. almost brothers...

523
00:44:04.733 --> 00:44:07.486
where these men find themselves.
by a trick of fate...

524
00:44:07.573 --> 00:44:09.928
on opposing sides in a great war?

525
00:44:10.253 --> 00:44:12.369
Then. on a given day...

526
00:44:12.453 --> 00:44:15.570
find themselves facing one another
on the very same battlefield?

527
00:44:18.053 --> 00:44:22.649
If the Greeks did not tell of such a story.
surely the Romans did.

528
00:44:24.333 --> 00:44:26.847
But. sir. I think it must be found
in the Bible.

529
00:44:27.293 --> 00:44:28.965
There isn't an officer on either side...

530
00:44:29.053 --> 00:44:32.409
who hasn't know someone wearing
the other uniform. I know that.

531
00:44:33.093 --> 00:44:34.765
But this morning...

532
00:44:35.613 --> 00:44:38.081
I looked through my glass
and saw the colors...

533
00:44:38.173 --> 00:44:41.722
of the 9th and 14th Virginia regiments
on those ridges before us...

534
00:44:41.813 --> 00:44:43.849
directly facing us. right over there.

535
00:44:44.373 --> 00:44:46.728
It was as if I could hear his voice.

536
00:44:47.573 --> 00:44:49.291
See his old crumpled hat.

537
00:44:50.933 --> 00:44:54.846
Armistead commands one of Pickett's
brigades and he's out there for sure.

538
00:44:56.893 --> 00:44:59.123
I somehow thought this day
would never come.

539
00:44:59.533 --> 00:45:01.728
I thought the war would be over
in a month.

540
00:45:01.813 --> 00:45:03.883
It's three years and how many more?

541
00:45:04.133 --> 00:45:06.852
Who could've dreamed
it could go on for so long?

542
00:45:09.813 --> 00:45:11.849
What would you do. Chamberlain?

543
00:45:13.653 --> 00:45:15.371
What do the books tell you to do?

544
00:45:19.093 --> 00:45:20.685
Now you go and rest up.

545
00:45:20.813 --> 00:45:22.929
Nothing's going to happen today anyway.

546
00:45:23.173 --> 00:45:26.643
Everybody's too tired. too hot.
too worn out. Both sides.

547
00:45:28.693 --> 00:45:31.048
We're placed in reserve. just over there.

548
00:45:31.133 --> 00:45:33.169
Thank you for your sentiments. sir.

549
00:46:04.213 --> 00:46:06.568
I just got back from the hospital.

550
00:46:07.733 --> 00:46:09.052
God-awful mess.

551
00:46:11.293 --> 00:46:12.612
They got no room.

552
00:46:13.533 --> 00:46:16.206
They got no shade.
They got men lying everywhere.

553
00:46:17.373 --> 00:46:20.365
They're cutting off arms and legs
in front of everybody.

554
00:46:23.093 --> 00:46:25.448
They ought to not do that in public.

555
00:46:27.533 --> 00:46:30.286
Men ought to have some privacy
at a time like that.

556
00:46:32.653 --> 00:46:33.688
You see Kilrain?

557
00:46:38.013 --> 00:46:39.082
How is he?

558
00:46:46.413 --> 00:46:47.402
He died.

559
00:46:53.973 --> 00:46:55.964
He died this morning before I got there.

560
00:46:58.613 --> 00:47:01.173
A couple of fellows were with him.

561
00:47:03.933 --> 00:47:05.924
He said to tell you goodbye.

562
00:47:07.893 --> 00:47:09.326
And that he was sorry.

563
00:47:21.093 --> 00:47:22.446
I tell you. Lawrence.

564
00:47:25.053 --> 00:47:26.771
I sure was fond of that man.

565
00:51:31.253 --> 00:51:34.006
General. please get down.
We cannot spare you.

566
00:51:34.333 --> 00:51:37.166
There are times when
a corps commander's life does not count.

567
00:52:50.933 --> 00:52:52.286
How are you. Lo?

568
00:52:54.973 --> 00:52:56.452
I'm fine. Dick.

569
00:52:59.773 --> 00:53:01.206
Well. that's good.

570
00:53:03.093 --> 00:53:04.492
How's the leg?

571
00:53:04.573 --> 00:53:05.972
It's all right.

572
00:53:07.173 --> 00:53:08.162
Can't walk.

573
00:53:08.333 --> 00:53:09.402
I'll have to ride.

574
00:53:09.493 --> 00:53:12.690
You can't do that.
You'll be the perfect target.

575
00:53:15.573 --> 00:53:18.724
We're going up there today
and we're going to break that line.

576
00:53:19.573 --> 00:53:24.203
When the Yankees run away. there'll be
an open road all the way to Washington.

577
00:53:26.933 --> 00:53:28.730
And maybe we'll win it today.

578
00:53:29.893 --> 00:53:31.929
And today will be the last day.

579
00:53:34.013 --> 00:53:35.048
Maybe today.

580
00:53:40.053 --> 00:53:41.691
I've got to ride up there.

581
00:53:45.613 --> 00:53:46.602
Well. Lo.

582
00:53:48.413 --> 00:53:49.892
I'll see you at the top.

583
00:54:10.613 --> 00:54:13.173
My God. Lo. Isn't it marvelous?

584
00:54:14.293 --> 00:54:15.965
I thought we missed it all.

585
00:54:17.173 --> 00:54:19.084
-Any questions?
-No.

586
00:54:19.173 --> 00:54:20.208
All right. then.

587
00:54:20.293 --> 00:54:22.932
When the firing ceases.
we step out real quick.

588
00:54:23.053 --> 00:54:26.329
No halting. no stopping to fire.
We want to get there quick as we can.

589
00:54:26.733 --> 00:54:27.802
What about Garnett?

590
00:54:27.893 --> 00:54:30.566
-What about him?
-He can't hardly walk.

591
00:54:30.813 --> 00:54:31.802
Damnation.

592
00:54:32.853 --> 00:54:35.970
George. order him not to make the charge.

593
00:54:36.133 --> 00:54:39.682
General Armistead. how can I do that?

594
00:54:46.173 --> 00:54:47.447
General Armistead. sir.

595
00:54:49.093 --> 00:54:50.572
My compliments.

596
00:54:57.053 --> 00:55:00.204
I hope Her Majesty's emissary
passed a comfortable night.

597
00:55:00.493 --> 00:55:02.211
Slept like the dead. sir.

598
00:55:02.293 --> 00:55:05.603
A baby. Slept like a newborn baby. sir.

599
00:55:10.093 --> 00:55:12.084
Lie still. men. Keep down.

600
00:55:14.053 --> 00:55:16.044
There's no safe place here.

601
00:55:18.933 --> 00:55:20.844
One spot's as good as the next.

602
00:55:28.853 --> 00:55:30.969
We've been firing for a good while. sir.

603
00:55:31.053 --> 00:55:35.410
It's apparent neither the federals nor we
are going to gain a clear advantage.

604
00:55:35.613 --> 00:55:38.173
If we continue to expend our ammunition
at this rate...

605
00:55:38.253 --> 00:55:40.767
we may endanger our ability
to support the advance.

606
00:55:41.013 --> 00:55:43.527
Did you not have enough ordinance
when this was begun?

607
00:55:43.973 --> 00:55:47.727
The federal fire compelled us to remove
the artillery train farther to the rear.

608
00:55:48.533 --> 00:55:51.331
It's taking us longer to refill the caissons.

609
00:55:51.413 --> 00:55:53.881
Sir. we must slow down our fire now...

610
00:55:53.973 --> 00:55:57.363
or we will have to cut back on the guns
sent in to support the infantry.

611
00:55:57.853 --> 00:55:58.922
Damn!

612
00:55:59.293 --> 00:56:03.684
I'll have to order General Pickett to halt
his attack until the guns get replenished.

613
00:56:03.773 --> 00:56:07.288
The trains have a little ammunition.
It'll take an hour to redistribute it.

614
00:56:07.373 --> 00:56:09.728
In the meanwhile.
the enemy would impound the top.

615
00:56:09.853 --> 00:56:11.002
The more we delay...

616
00:56:11.093 --> 00:56:14.085
the more time the federals have
to strengthen their own lines.

617
00:56:14.173 --> 00:56:17.131
And even if we recover more supplies
from the ordinance train...

618
00:56:17.213 --> 00:56:20.125
how much more damage can we inflict
on them than they on us?

619
00:56:20.533 --> 00:56:23.650
They're bringing in fresh batteries
as quickly as we drive them off.

620
00:56:23.733 --> 00:56:25.883
Just get some more ammunition
and keep it hot.

621
00:56:26.413 --> 00:56:28.688
I can't send Pickett's division
or the others...

622
00:56:28.813 --> 00:56:31.646
until we clear some of those guns
off that ridge.

623
00:57:06.973 --> 00:57:10.727
I'm told you are descended
from an illustrious military family.

624
00:57:11.373 --> 00:57:13.364
Who told you that? Kemper?

625
00:57:13.773 --> 00:57:16.765
He tells me it was your uncle
who defended Fort McHenry...

626
00:57:16.853 --> 00:57:18.491
during the War of 1812.

627
00:57:19.293 --> 00:57:23.764
And that he was therefore the guardian
of the original <i>Star-Spangled Banner</i>.

628
00:57:23.893 --> 00:57:26.851
I must say.
I do appreciate the irony of it all.

629
00:57:27.493 --> 00:57:28.972
Colonel Fremantle.

630
00:57:29.613 --> 00:57:33.970
It does not begin or end with my uncle
or myself.

631
00:57:35.253 --> 00:57:37.483
We're all sons of Virginia here.

632
00:57:41.013 --> 00:57:43.083
That major out there
commanding the cannon:

633
00:57:43.373 --> 00:57:44.522
That's James Dearing.

634
00:57:44.933 --> 00:57:48.482
First in his class at West Point.
before Virginia seceded.

635
00:57:48.733 --> 00:57:51.167
And the boy over there
with the color guard.

636
00:57:51.773 --> 00:57:54.287
That's Private Robert Tyler Jones.

637
00:57:54.653 --> 00:57:58.532
His grandfather was
President of the United States.

638
00:57:59.653 --> 00:58:03.282
The colonel behind me.
that's Colonel William Aylett.

639
00:58:04.373 --> 00:58:06.204
Now. his great grandfather...

640
00:58:06.933 --> 00:58:09.242
was the Virginian Patrick Henry.

641
00:58:12.293 --> 00:58:15.968
It was Patrick Henry
who said to your King George lll:

642
00:58:16.693 --> 00:58:19.082
"Give me liberty or give me death."

643
00:58:23.373 --> 00:58:25.091
There are boys here from...

644
00:58:25.653 --> 00:58:26.881
Norfolk.

645
00:58:27.893 --> 00:58:29.326
Portsmouth.

646
00:58:29.973 --> 00:58:32.692
Small hamlets along the James River.

647
00:58:33.613 --> 00:58:36.173
From Charlottesville and Fredericksburg.

648
00:58:36.373 --> 00:58:38.284
The Shenandoah Valley.

649
00:58:40.693 --> 00:58:43.287
Mostly they're all veteran soldiers now.

650
00:58:43.413 --> 00:58:46.007
The cowards and shirkers are long gone.

651
00:58:47.893 --> 00:58:50.885
Every man here knows his duty.

652
00:58:52.653 --> 00:58:57.169
They would make this charge
even without an officer to lead them.

653
00:59:00.933 --> 00:59:03.288
They know the gravity of the situation.

654
00:59:03.893 --> 00:59:06.168
And the mettle of their foe.

655
00:59:07.853 --> 00:59:10.890
They know that this day's work...

656
00:59:12.853 --> 00:59:15.003
will be desperate and deadly.

657
00:59:16.453 --> 00:59:19.525
They know that for many of them...

658
00:59:20.053 --> 00:59:22.123
this will be their last charge.

659
00:59:24.093 --> 00:59:28.132
But not one of them needs to be told
what is expected of him.

660
00:59:29.013 --> 00:59:31.811
They are all willing to make
the supreme sacrifice...

661
00:59:33.333 --> 00:59:37.087
to achieve victory here.

662
00:59:39.213 --> 00:59:42.842
The crowning victory
and the end of this war.

663
00:59:46.013 --> 00:59:47.412
We are all here.

664
00:59:50.133 --> 00:59:52.931
You may tell them
when you return to your country...

665
00:59:53.613 --> 00:59:57.242
that all Virginia was here on this day.

666
01:00:26.213 --> 01:00:27.885
A message from Alexander.

667
01:00:28.093 --> 01:00:31.722
"Hurry up. for God's sake.
or the artillery can't help you."

668
01:00:33.533 --> 01:00:35.091
Your order. sir?

669
01:00:38.293 --> 01:00:41.888
General Longstreet.
should I commence the attack?

670
01:00:47.773 --> 01:00:49.968
I shall lead my division forward. sir.

671
01:01:20.533 --> 01:01:23.445
For the glory of Virginia.
form your brigade.

672
01:01:28.613 --> 01:01:29.966
Gentlemen...

673
01:01:31.173 --> 01:01:32.686
form your battalions.

674
01:01:35.373 --> 01:01:37.682
Battalion. forward!

675
01:03:38.053 --> 01:03:42.046
Father. into your hands.
I commend my spirit.

676
01:04:04.853 --> 01:04:08.766
Up. men! Up! And to your posts!

677
01:04:10.373 --> 01:04:12.603
And let no man forget today...

678
01:04:13.293 --> 01:04:16.968
that you are from old Virginia.

679
01:04:18.613 --> 01:04:22.811
Virginia !

680
01:04:28.853 --> 01:04:30.127
Virginians!

681
01:04:34.933 --> 01:04:37.970
For your lands! For your homes!

682
01:04:40.558 --> 01:04:42.037
For your sweethearts!

683
01:04:43.518 --> 01:04:44.746
For your wives!

684
01:04:47.358 --> 01:04:49.553
For Virginia !

685
01:04:51.798 --> 01:04:53.390
Forward!

686
01:04:53.558 --> 01:04:56.118
Forward!

687
01:05:01.318 --> 01:05:02.512
March!

688
01:10:41.558 --> 01:10:43.753
Come on. men!
And keep your heads down!

689
01:10:44.638 --> 01:10:46.515
-Reload!
-Reloading!

690
01:13:30.078 --> 01:13:33.388
Clear the lines! To the front. boys!
One. two!

691
01:13:34.798 --> 01:13:36.675
We are with you. General!

692
01:13:38.038 --> 01:13:39.437
Come on. boy!

693
01:13:43.678 --> 01:13:45.077
Come on. boy!

694
01:13:45.398 --> 01:13:46.751
The glasses!

695
01:14:35.398 --> 01:14:37.354
Let's go! Over the fence!

696
01:14:46.318 --> 01:14:47.751
Fill that gap!

697
01:14:51.478 --> 01:14:52.957
Over the fence!

698
01:15:18.398 --> 01:15:20.036
Come on. men! Move!

699
01:15:20.238 --> 01:15:24.436
But save your strength for the attack
and get over the fence. quickly!

700
01:15:46.518 --> 01:15:50.113
Give them double canisters! That's it!
Double canisters!

701
01:15:53.558 --> 01:15:55.947
Get up. men! Fire!

702
01:16:08.958 --> 01:16:10.869
Give them the cold steel!

703
01:16:54.158 --> 01:16:56.626
Take that to General Longstreet
quick as you can.

704
01:16:56.718 --> 01:16:58.151
With my compliments.

705
01:16:59.398 --> 01:17:01.070
Damnation! Come on!

706
01:17:13.758 --> 01:17:14.986
Do it!

707
01:17:15.718 --> 01:17:17.197
Fire away. men!

708
01:17:17.638 --> 01:17:18.957
Move it up!

709
01:17:19.558 --> 01:17:21.549
Steady! Keep that line there!

710
01:17:23.798 --> 01:17:25.789
Keep up your fire! Colonel!

711
01:17:29.278 --> 01:17:31.633
Bring your men forward.
We'll flank these bastards.

712
01:17:31.718 --> 01:17:32.946
Bring the men forward.

713
01:17:33.038 --> 01:17:34.915
By God. we'll flank them.

714
01:17:38.598 --> 01:17:39.951
Damn it all!

715
01:17:42.838 --> 01:17:44.556
I will not be moved...

716
01:17:45.118 --> 01:17:46.915
until this engagement is decided.

717
01:17:48.158 --> 01:17:50.956
Get me a tourniquet
before I bleed to death.

718
01:17:56.598 --> 01:17:58.031
Forward. boys!

719
01:18:20.758 --> 01:18:21.873
What are you doing?

720
01:18:22.198 --> 01:18:24.428
You've got to come up and help us.

721
01:18:24.838 --> 01:18:26.590
In God's name. they're flanking us.

722
01:18:26.678 --> 01:18:29.112
Coming down on the right
and firing right into us.

723
01:18:30.038 --> 01:18:32.393
Head for the trees.
Head right for the center.

724
01:18:32.598 --> 01:18:35.317
I'll call for double-quick. Nobody waits.

725
01:18:35.558 --> 01:18:37.753
-Everybody goes.
-All right.

726
01:18:39.398 --> 01:18:42.071
Boys! At the double-quick!

727
01:18:45.838 --> 01:18:47.396
March!

728
01:18:49.038 --> 01:18:50.676
Come on! Together!

729
01:19:13.398 --> 01:19:16.754
Come on. boys! They're breaking!

730
01:19:24.198 --> 01:19:26.189
Forward to the wall!

731
01:19:46.038 --> 01:19:47.790
Get them to the ridge. boys!

732
01:20:18.838 --> 01:20:21.398
Move out. boys! Move out!

733
01:20:25.398 --> 01:20:26.672
Come on. boy.

734
01:20:27.038 --> 01:20:29.393
What will you think of yourself tomorrow?

735
01:20:30.238 --> 01:20:31.557
Virginians!

736
01:20:35.158 --> 01:20:38.912
We're staying. Who will come with me?

737
01:20:40.118 --> 01:20:41.597
Let's go. boys!

738
01:20:52.678 --> 01:20:54.396
That's the style. Lo.

739
01:20:54.838 --> 01:20:56.396
That's the style!

740
01:22:13.918 --> 01:22:15.476
The day is ours. men!

741
01:22:15.758 --> 01:22:18.591
Turn the cannons on them !
Turn the cannons!

742
01:23:49.038 --> 01:23:50.471
Break them. Lo!

743
01:24:00.198 --> 01:24:03.315
What's happening?
I can't see what's happening to my boys!

744
01:24:04.798 --> 01:24:06.834
What's happening to my boys?

745
01:24:07.078 --> 01:24:08.636
Major. give me your glasses.

746
01:24:13.678 --> 01:24:16.112
There's a rebel. Take him prisoner.

747
01:25:52.598 --> 01:25:55.271
Will you help me up. please?

748
01:25:55.598 --> 01:25:58.556
Sir. could you tell me what your name is?
Who you are?

749
01:26:00.318 --> 01:26:02.752
I would like to speak to General Hancock.

750
01:26:03.198 --> 01:26:08.431
Do you know where General Hancock
may be found?

751
01:26:09.838 --> 01:26:12.432
I'm sorry. sir. The general is down.

752
01:26:12.638 --> 01:26:14.788
-He's been hit.
-No!

753
01:26:15.998 --> 01:26:17.590
Not both of us.

754
01:26:19.038 --> 01:26:20.994
Not all of us.

755
01:26:22.238 --> 01:26:23.796
Please. God.

756
01:26:23.878 --> 01:26:27.188
Sir. we're having a surgeon come
as quickly as we can.

757
01:26:30.118 --> 01:26:32.188
Can you hear me. son?

758
01:26:32.358 --> 01:26:34.713
Yes. sir. I can hear you.

759
01:26:35.678 --> 01:26:38.590
Will you tell General Hancock...

760
01:26:40.158 --> 01:26:44.197
that General Armistead sends his regrets?

761
01:26:46.798 --> 01:26:48.629
Will you tell him...

762
01:26:49.758 --> 01:26:53.831
how very sorry I am?

763
01:26:56.318 --> 01:26:59.913
I will tell him. sir. I will tell him.

764
01:27:14.878 --> 01:27:16.470
General Webb. sir.

765
01:27:59.518 --> 01:28:01.588
Let go of the horse. Major.

766
01:28:02.078 --> 01:28:04.308
Major Sorrel. I said let go of the horse.

767
01:28:04.398 --> 01:28:06.468
Now you form up here.
put fire down on them.

768
01:28:06.558 --> 01:28:08.913
They're coming
and I'm going to meet them.

769
01:28:10.758 --> 01:28:12.635
Captain Goree. Come on!

770
01:28:33.038 --> 01:28:35.996
General. what are your orders. sir?
What do you want me to do?

771
01:28:36.358 --> 01:28:37.677
Where do you want me to go?

772
01:28:46.718 --> 01:28:49.027
You've got to pull back. General.
Pull back. sir.

773
01:28:49.118 --> 01:28:51.348
Place the guns. Bring up the guns!

774
01:28:56.398 --> 01:28:57.433
God!

775
01:29:03.758 --> 01:29:05.191
How are you. T.J.?

776
01:29:05.478 --> 01:29:07.150
I'm tolerable. sir.

777
01:29:10.558 --> 01:29:11.877
They aren't coming.

778
01:29:12.078 --> 01:29:13.272
Too bad.

779
01:29:15.958 --> 01:29:16.947
Yes. sir.

780
01:29:18.758 --> 01:29:19.952
General.

781
01:29:20.918 --> 01:29:22.590
I'll tell you plain.

782
01:29:23.838 --> 01:29:25.590
There are times when you worry me.

783
01:29:27.718 --> 01:29:29.754
No good trying to get yourself killed.

784
01:29:30.238 --> 01:29:32.547
The Lord will come for you
in his own good time.

785
01:29:35.878 --> 01:29:37.789
What are the orders. sir?

786
01:29:41.998 --> 01:29:45.786
Prepare for defense.
but the Yankees aren't coming.

787
01:29:48.638 --> 01:29:50.071
Come on. boys.

788
01:29:56.158 --> 01:29:58.672
I have the figures from Pickett's command.

789
01:29:59.838 --> 01:30:01.635
General Armistead is missing.

790
01:30:02.318 --> 01:30:05.549
General Garnett.
missing and figured to be dead. sir.

791
01:30:06.438 --> 01:30:09.032
General Kemper is down.
seriously wounded.

792
01:30:09.998 --> 01:30:15.026
Sir. of the 13 colonels in Pickett's division.
seven are dead and six are wounded.

793
01:30:15.118 --> 01:30:17.586
No more. You tell me the rest later.

794
01:30:29.558 --> 01:30:31.435
-Major?
-Yes. sir.

795
01:30:31.638 --> 01:30:34.311
Is that General Kemper
there bearing toward us?

796
01:30:34.878 --> 01:30:36.755
I believe it to be. sir.

797
01:30:40.798 --> 01:30:42.197
General Kemper.

798
01:30:43.678 --> 01:30:45.669
I do hope you are not seriously injured.

799
01:30:49.438 --> 01:30:52.635
They tell me that it's mortal. General.

800
01:30:52.918 --> 01:30:55.432
I do pray God that it is not the case.

801
01:30:55.798 --> 01:30:57.231
Is there anything I can do?

802
01:30:57.598 --> 01:31:00.396
There's nothing more you can do for me.

803
01:31:03.038 --> 01:31:08.271
But. General Lee. will you see to it
that full justice is done for my men...

804
01:31:11.118 --> 01:31:13.427
who made this charge today?

805
01:31:14.558 --> 01:31:15.832
I will do so. sir.

806
01:31:15.918 --> 01:31:17.590
Thank you. General.

807
01:31:22.238 --> 01:31:23.671
Thank you. General.

808
01:31:26.398 --> 01:31:27.831
It's my fault.

809
01:31:29.798 --> 01:31:31.072
It's my fault.

810
01:31:34.078 --> 01:31:36.353
I thought we were invincible.

811
01:31:37.158 --> 01:31:38.227
Friends.

812
01:31:39.358 --> 01:31:40.791
It is all my fault.

813
01:31:42.118 --> 01:31:43.107
Hear me.

814
01:31:43.798 --> 01:31:45.516
Hear me. I pray you.

815
01:31:45.958 --> 01:31:47.630
It is entirely my fault.

816
01:31:49.198 --> 01:31:50.392
Hear me.

817
01:31:50.598 --> 01:31:52.395
Hear me. Please. friends.

818
01:31:53.118 --> 01:31:54.551
We must rest now.

819
01:31:55.358 --> 01:31:57.394
We must retire
and fight again another day.

820
01:31:57.478 --> 01:31:59.628
And there will be another day.

821
01:31:59.958 --> 01:32:02.711
Meanwhile. friends.
we must show good order.

822
01:32:02.878 --> 01:32:05.153
Never let them see you run.
Do you hear me?

823
01:32:05.438 --> 01:32:07.076
Never let them see you run.

824
01:32:07.158 --> 01:32:09.831
Let us hit them again.
Let us reform and hit them again.

825
01:32:09.918 --> 01:32:11.033
I know we can do it.

826
01:32:13.998 --> 01:32:15.750
God bless you. gentlemen.

827
01:32:20.198 --> 01:32:23.110
They're forming over there. Major.
I do fear they may attack.

828
01:32:23.198 --> 01:32:24.426
Yes. sir.

829
01:32:26.838 --> 01:32:28.157
General Pickett.

830
01:32:28.998 --> 01:32:33.389
You may reform to the rear of this ridge
and set up a defensive position.

831
01:32:38.598 --> 01:32:42.147
General Pickett. sir.
You must look to your division.

832
01:32:49.598 --> 01:32:50.713
General Lee.

833
01:32:53.758 --> 01:32:55.191
I have no division.

834
01:34:01.918 --> 01:34:03.510
General....

835
01:34:14.918 --> 01:34:16.749
We will withdraw...

836
01:34:17.838 --> 01:34:21.228
as soon as we have secured
all those wounded...

837
01:34:23.678 --> 01:34:25.908
who are well enough to be moved.

838
01:34:30.038 --> 01:34:31.869
If we can reach the Potomac...

839
01:34:33.758 --> 01:34:35.828
and cross over into Virginia...

840
01:34:37.598 --> 01:34:40.317
there will be no more immediate danger.

841
01:34:42.918 --> 01:34:44.510
But I'll need your help. Pete.

842
01:34:51.998 --> 01:34:54.387
I'm so very tired.

843
01:34:56.998 --> 01:34:58.192
What can I do. sir?

844
01:35:04.558 --> 01:35:05.752
General?

845
01:35:15.838 --> 01:35:18.227
We must look to our own deportment.

846
01:35:22.558 --> 01:35:26.107
The spirit of the army is still very good.
Very good indeed.

847
01:35:30.278 --> 01:35:32.473
We will do better another time.

848
01:35:37.518 --> 01:35:41.272
They do not die for us. Not for us.

849
01:35:43.838 --> 01:35:45.908
That at least is a blessing.

850
01:35:48.798 --> 01:35:50.550
If this war goes on....

851
01:35:51.798 --> 01:35:52.913
And it will.

852
01:35:53.598 --> 01:35:54.792
It will.

853
01:35:56.478 --> 01:35:58.673
What else can we do but go on. you and I?

854
01:36:00.158 --> 01:36:03.514
It's always the same question forever.

855
01:36:05.238 --> 01:36:07.035
What else can we do?

856
01:36:08.318 --> 01:36:10.070
If they fight...

857
01:36:11.158 --> 01:36:12.796
we must fight with them.

858
01:36:14.838 --> 01:36:17.193
And does it matter. after all. who wins?

859
01:36:19.518 --> 01:36:21.713
Was that ever really the question?

860
01:36:25.038 --> 01:36:27.757
Will almighty God
ask that question in the end?

861
01:47:31.358 --> 01:47:34.395
Subtitles conformed by
SOFTITLER

862
01:47:34.718 --> 01:47:36.151
English
